{"cursor":"7469","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox company\n| company_name = Eurocom company_logo = caption = The final Eurocom logo\n| (2006â2012) company_type = Video game developer fate = Bankruptcy foundation =\n| October 1988 founder = Mat Sneap, Chris Shrigley, Hugh Binns, Tim Rogers, Neil\n| Baldwin defunct = 6 December 2012 company_slogan =\n| location = Derby, United Kingdom key_people = industry = Computer and video\n| games products = revenue = owner = num_employees = Approx.250 parent =\n}}\n\n'Eurocom' (formerly 'Eurocom Entertainment Software') was a British video game\ndeveloper founded in October 1988 by Mat Sneap, Chris Shrigley, Hugh Binns, Tim\nRogers and Neil Baldwin, to specifically develop games for the Nintendo\nEntertainment System. Since then, Eurocom has expanded to several other\nplatforms including handheld game systems and most major video game consoles.\n\nThe company was once famous for its arcade to console ports, but is now\nbetter known for working with licensed properties such as [[Pirates of the\nCaribbean: At World's End (video game)|Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's\nEnd]], [[Ice Age: The Meltdown#Video game|Ice Age 2: The Meltdown]], the\n[[James Bond (games)|James Bond 007]] series, and [[Batman Begins (video\ngame)|Batman Begins]].\n\nOn 23 November 2012, Eurocom laid off around 75% of their 200 employees, in a\nstatement company director Hugh Binns said \"... Eurocom are undertaking a\nrestructuring which I regret to say has meant we've made the majority of our\nworkforce redundant today ...\", attributing a \"steep decline in demand for\nconsole games\", and \"...will be focusing mainly on mobile opportunities moving\nforward.\" http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/11/23/007-legends-dev-hit-\nby-redundancies\n\nOn 6 December 2012, the company laid off its remaining staff and ceased trading. http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-12-07-james-bond-developer-\neurocom-makes-remaining-staff-redundant-ceases-trading\n","linknr":194,"url":"Eurocom","recorded":1375074862,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Eurocom&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Eurocom&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Eurocom_(disambiguation)","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Eurocom&action=edit","/wiki/Help:Introduction_to_referencing/1","/wiki/Template:Citation_needed","/wiki/Wikipedia:Verifiability#Burden_of_evidence","/wiki/File:Eurocom.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/3/3f/Eurocom.png","/wiki/Types_of_business_entity","/wiki/Video_game_developer","/wiki/Video_game_industry","/wiki/Bankruptcy","/wiki/1988_in_video_gaming#Business","/wiki/2012_in_video_gaming#Events","#cite_note-EuroGClosure-1","/wiki/Derby","/wiki/United_Kingdom","/wiki/United_Kingdom","/wiki/Video_game_developer","/wiki/Nintendo_Entertainment_System","/wiki/Handheld_game_console","/wiki/Video_game_console","/wiki/Arcade_game","/wiki/Pirates_of_the_Caribbean:_At_World%27s_End_(video_game)","/wiki/Ice_Age:_The_Meltdown#Video_game","/wiki/James_Bond_(games)","/wiki/Batman_Begins_(video_game)","#cite_note-EuroGClosure-1","#cite_note-2","